Intellectual merit &ndash;

Detailed computational simulations were performed on of a variety of bulk electrolytes with a view to optimizing the stability of the bulk forms as well as the stability of interfaces of the electrolyte with pure ideal Li or Na metal anodes. The focus on solid state electrolyte materials designed for use with pure Li or Na anodes, was motivated by growing evidence that these offer significant stability and efficiency advantages over the battery technology available today.  For example, in conjunction with experimental collaborators, we studied the electrolyte Li2OHCl which has significant Li ion conductivity at temperatures somewhat above room temperature.  At these warm temperatures, the system is known to have a disordered cubic structure.   The disorder includes both the orientations of the OH bonds and the distribution of Li ion vacancies.  In order to well-represent the disorder in this material, simulation methods were adapted with the help of sampling techniques.  Additionally, molecular dynamics simulations were analyzed, finding that ion motion in Li2OHCl is highly correlated in an interesting way.  The OH bond orientations participate in a sort of gating mechanism for Li ion conduction.

Broader impacts &ndash;

The broader impacts of this work include possible technological developments in battery technology and careful training of new computational scientists.

